When Jin Guangyao's honeyed words took their poisonous effects, and he only saw Jiang Cheng's amplified flaws, so, so confident in the words of his previous friend and his own judgment.

Mirrors never break of their own volition. Mirrors are nothing, only reflecting what has been put in front of them, and Lan Xichen hates because he sees who he used to be.

Lan Xichen, Lan Xichen, the so-called dawn that lights and warms everything he graces his presence with, but a man swayed by rumour and reputation. They are all mortal flesh in the end, Jiang Cheng scowls in disappointment.

The distant stars, a universe away, are easy to detest, the perfect sculpture ceases to be related to and becomes a target for mockery. Jiang Cheng had narrowed his eyes, let his face twist as he sneered back, Lan Xichen's cold expression seared into his memory.

The Lan Xichen, whom Jiang Cheng once hated, whom he witnessed the older man sweep a dismissive, judgmental look his way when Lan Xichen assumed Jiang Cheng wasn't looking - and Jiang Cheng felt the fires within him burn, felt himself loathe.

"You must be so happy together!" says the voice that hides its envious whisper - "you must feel so lucky" - for the great Lan Xichen to deign to marry Jiang Cheng, for Jiang Cheng to have the fortune of being loved by someone like him - handsome, gentle, capable, flawless.
